3.9  DEPARTMENT OF AUTOMOTIVE & MARINE 
ENGINEERING 
The Department of Automotive and Marine Engineering 
was established in 2005 at NED University of Engineering 
and Technology, Karachi, to meet the growing demands of 
Pakistan’s expanding automotive sector, with Karachi 
serving as the hub of automotive activity. Recognizing the 
need for advanced education in this field, the Department 
introduced the Master’s in Automotive Engineering 
programme in June 2009. This postgraduate programme 
offers an in-depth study of automotive engineering, 
covering 
engine 
systems, 
vehicle 
aerodynamics, 
automotive materials and their properties, as well as 
analysis of transportation systems. The Department offers 
two core areas of specialization: Automotive Design and 
Automotive Manufacturing, each structured to equip 
graduates with the knowledge and skills required to meet 
contemporary industry challenges and contribute to 
technological advancements in the automotive sector. The 
programme is designed to achieve the following goals: 
• 
Provide automotive engineers with hands-on 
experience in teamwork and project management 
to plan and execute complex automotive projects 
effectively. 
• 
Develop a solid grasp of related disciplines, 
management, and human factors essential for 
designing and marketing modern automotive 
systems. 
• 
Enhance the technical competence of automotive 
engineers through advanced courses that build 
analytical thinking, innovation, and problem-solving 
skills. 
• 
Broaden their professional outlook by engaging 
them in interdisciplinary activities encompassing the 
design, testing, and manufacturing of advanced 
automotive systems. 
3.9.1 Departmental Facilities 
To support the programme, the Department is equipped 
with several state-of-the-art laboratories, including the 
Combustion and Emission Lab, Body and Suspension Lab, 
Auto-Electronics Lab, Basic Electronics Lab, and Computer 
Lab. The laboratories are well-furnished with modern 
equipment related to vehicle ride and handling, emission 
systems, and automotive electronics, enabling students to 
gain practical and experimental exposure aligned with 
industry standards. For research and advanced learning, 
the Department provides facilities for experimental 
investigation and simulation-based studies. The Computer 
Lab is equipped with CAD and FEA software to enhance 
students’ design and analysis skills. In addition, dedicated 
software tools are regularly utilized by faculty members in 
teaching advanced-level courses, ensuring that students 
are well-prepared for modern engineering challenges. The 
prospective students of this programme would primarily 
consist of graduate engineers currently employed in 
automotive sector as well as those having bachelor’s 
degrees in Automotive, Mechanical, or Industrial & 
Manufacturing Engineering. 
